# 1️⃣ Identity & Access Management (IAM)

Identity & Access Management ensures that only authorized users can access specific resources using the **principle of least privilege**.

---

## 🔐 Password Policy Configuration

Tool: `secpol.msc`  
Path:  
`Account Policies → Password Policy`

Recommended Configuration:
- Minimum password length: 12–14 characters  
- Enforce password history: 5–10 passwords  
- Maximum password age: 60–90 days  
- Password complexity: Enabled  

Verify configuration:
```powershell
net accounts

🔐 Account Lockout Policy

Path:
Account Policies → Account Lockout Policy

Recommended:

Lockout threshold: 5 failed attempts
Lockout duration: 15–30 minutes
Reset counter after: 15 minutes
Purpose: Prevents automated login attacks.

🔐 Managing Default & Privileged Accounts

Disable built-in administrator:
net user administrator /active:no

Best Practices:

Rename default Administrator account
Disable Guest account
Remove inactive users
Regularly audit privileged accounts
Check administrators group:
net localgroup administrators

🔐 Least Privilege Implementation

Remove unnecessary users from Local Administrators group
Use separate admin accounts for administrative tasks
Avoid using Domain Admin for daily activities
Apply Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)

🔐 Credential Protection

Enable Credential Guard
Disable NTLM where possible
Prefer Kerberos authentication
Enforce Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

2️⃣ Network Management

Network hardening prevents unauthorized access and lateral movement.

🌐 Windows Firewall Configuration
Enable firewall profiles:

Get-NetFirewallProfile
Set-NetFirewallProfile -Profile Domain,Public,Private -Enabled True

Best Practices:
Block inbound traffic by default
Allow only necessary ports (e.g., 443 for HTTPS)
Restrict administrative services

🌐 Secure Remote Desktop (RDP)
Open RDP settings:

SystemPropertiesRemote.exe

Security Measures:
Enable Network Level Authentication (NLA)
Restrict RDP via firewall rules
Allow only specific IP addresses
Disable RDP if not required

🌐 Disable SMBv1
Disable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName SMB1Protocol
Reason: SMBv1 is outdated and vulnerable to ransomware exploits.

🌐 Disable Unnecessary Services

Open Services Manager:
services.msc
Review and disable:
Remote Registry
Telnet
Print Spooler (if unused)
Reducing active services lowers attack surface.

3️⃣ Application Management

Applications are common attack vectors; controlling execution reduces compromise risk.

🧩 Application Control (AppLocker / WDAC)
Allow only signed or approved applications
Restrict unknown executables
Block unauthorized scripts

🧩 Remove Unnecessary Software
List installed programs:
Get-WmiObject -Class Win32_Product
Remove unused software via:
Control Panel → Programs & Features

🧩 Restrict PowerShell Usage
Set execution policy:
Set-ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned

Enable:
Script Block Logging
Module Logging
Purpose: Detect and monitor malicious PowerShell activity.

🧩 Regular Application Updates
Ensure regular updates for:
Web browsers
Microsoft Office
Third-party applications
Outdated software is a primary attack vector.

4️⃣ Storage & Compute Security

Protecting stored data and system resources prevents data breaches and unauthorized access.

💾 Enable BitLocker
Check status:
manage-bde -status
Best Practices:
Encrypt system drive
Store recovery keys securely
Use TPM for hardware-backed encryption

💾 Configure NTFS Permissions
Path:
Right-click Folder → Properties → Security → Advanced

Best Practices:
Remove "Everyone" group
Assign permissions based on roles
Enable auditing for sensitive folders

💾 Disable Autorun
Open:
gpedit.msc

Path:
Computer Configuration → Administrative Templates → Windows Components → AutoPlay Policies
Purpose: Prevent USB-based malware execution.

💾 Resource Monitoring

Use:
Task Manager
Resource Monitor
Performance Monitor

Purpose:
Detect abnormal CPU, memory, or disk activity indicating compromise.

5️⃣ Importance of Updating Windows

Regular updates patch vulnerabilities and protect systems from exploitation.

🛡 Why Updates Are Critical

Patch zero-day vulnerabilities
Prevent ransomware exploitation
Fix privilege escalation flaws
Update Defender security intelligence
Check update logs:
Get-WindowsUpdateLog
Enterprise-level solutions:
WSUS
Centralized patch management systems
Unpatched systems are one of the most common causes of security breaches.

